@node gene "General News!!"

Well, it's certainly been a quiet month as far as the CD32 goes, with
only a handful of new games titles being released.  Hopefully this
situation will be rectified next month!!

Last month, I asked for readers of this magazine to drop me a note if
they had FMV on their CD32's....  Well, it seems that magazines like AUI
are correct to not use FMV on their disks yet, because I only got one
measily reply.  If I didn't know better, I would think that nobody was
reading this!!!!!  Seriously though, What are your opinions?  I really
would like some input!!   To all you Americans, are you able to get the
FMV module yet??

The new edition of CD32 Gamer is out now, but has already gone up in
price from £4 to £5, which is a bit strange seeing that there is much
less on the cover CD.  Originally, the magazine was going to be
published quarterly, but now it's bi-monthly.  Hopefully, if the high
cover price is going to continue they will include better stuff on the
disk.  After all, the CD is the reason that most people buy the CD.

@endnode
@node comm "The Big C="

At last, conformation has arrived of Commodores situation.  It has come
to light that SAMSUNG, the monitor manufacturer has bought C= outright.
It would seem that Samsung has sufficient financial power to inject new
life into the machine, whilst not affecting it in any adverse way.
Hopefully, they will start to bundle monitors with their machines.  It
has also been stated that once up to full power, the long awaited AAA
(Triple A) chipset will be ready within a month.  Surely a tall order,
but that is what they are saying...

There was also the worrying reports that Phillips (CD-I) had bought all
rights to the CD32.  Fortunately these dispersed rapidly.  It seems that
the rumours stemmed from a meeting between C= and Phillips with concerns
to the CD32.  It's purpose was, in fact to ensure that future Video CD
releases would be white book, and not in the format that Phillips had
previously been using which caused the films to jump when used on
suitably equipped CD32's.  (EG Patriot Games).
@endnode
@node cont "Theres a new CD32 Controller About!!!"

At long last, someone has released a replacement joypad which no CD32
user should be without.  It's called the Super CD32 and is manufactured
by Competition Pro.

It features all of the controls found in the normal pad, so there will
be no incompatability problems with either games or FMV movies.  Plus,
it has additional functions which allow you to slow down a game, have
autofire, or the ability to have turbo fire, which means you will be
able to destroy the baddies much quicker.

The Super CD32 pad wins hands down over the normal pad, and at £19.99,
is a fair price too!!
@endnode
@node fmvp "New ROMS for FMV!!"

Apparantly, the jumping, and general loss of sync found when using CDI
films on the CD32 can now be solved by getting replacement ROMS from
Commodore.  The cost is said to be about £5, but you will need an
authorised engineer to fit them....  If you return the FMV module to
your dealer, they should be able to do the upgrade for you.
