@node chuc "Chuck Rock II"

             Chuck Rock II           Core Design             £30


It's nice to see a sequel which is good.  Especially when the original
was an absolute turkey.  Chuck Rock 2 opens with a brilliant cartoon
style animation, which is equally as good as similar, on-screen cartoons
such as The Flintstones.  You play Chuck junior, and it is your mission
to romp through the prehistoric fun-filled levels in an attempt to
rescue your dad, who has been kidnapped by his arch enemy Brick Jagger.

The gameplay, whilst simplistic is a lot of fun, and for once, the awful
CD32 controller does not hinder you too much.  The graphics are quite
nice, as are the sound effects, all of which will probably keep you
coming back for more.  You could do a lot worse than to get this!!


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ****
@endnode
@node fire "Fire and Ice"

              Fire and Ice            Renegade             £25

One of the old classics makes a welcome return to the CD32.  You play
Cool Coyote who must travel the 30 levels rescuing his pups whilst
killing a whole host of baddies to obtain the key that allows you to
leave the level.  The graphics and soundtrack are perfect, and there is
even an option to use the same music as in the original, which is great
for all of you nostalgic old timers out there.

However, Fire and Ice has too major problems.  First of course, as with
almost every other game is the crappy controller.  A lot of the game
requires precise movement, and this is just not possible.  Fortunately,
a normal joystick will allow you much more control.  Secondly, for some
reason, the screen position is offset to the right.  This is really
annoying, and as far as I can see, there is no way of fixing this.
Still though, Fire and Ice is a very enjoyable game.


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ***
@endnode
@node guns "Gunship 2000"

              Gunship 2000            Microprose           £30

When I spoke to one of the representatives on the Microprose stand at
the ECTS, all he could talk about was the Silicon Graphics rendered
introduction.  I can see why, but unfortunately it is not because it is
particularly impressive.  The reason is because the game is seemingly no
different.  He told me that it was a direct port to CD of the original
game, but according to the packaging it definately is AGA.  Now, this it
may be, but not so that you could notice it.  All I could see was that
the game was slowed down a great deal, even with all of the terrain
options on low quality.
The gameplay is now extremely difficult, and using the different number
of combinations of direction+button to control the helicopter is not
instinctive and will take a lot of practise.  The sound effects are now
digital quality, so sound a lot better, but that, to me does not
constitute a major upgrade.
As for the intro, well even if it was rendered on an SGI, Microprose
have made a hash of converting it to run on the CD32.  It is one of the
worst examples of CDXL that I have so far seen.  It just looks like a
collection of line sketches that have been joined together.
In conclusion, Gunship is a great game, but this release does it no
justice.  By all means buy it if you do not already have the original
version, but if you do, you will just be wasting your money.


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ***
@endnode
@node huma "Humans 1+2"

              Humans 1+2              Gametek               £30

Gametek's second release for the CD32 is much better than the first,(I
will leave it to you to find out what the first was!!).  It is a
combination of both of the Lemmings-Like puzzlers that were originally
released 2 years ago.  In the game, you control a tribe of men who have
to use their various abilities together in order to get through levels.
EG A stationary man that can be climbed over to reach previously
inaccesible areas.  In the game you can pick up various objects to aid
your task like sticks to pole vault with, and burning objects to ward
off dinosaurs.  The game has hundreds of levels, and only the most
addicted players will ever get throught them all.  As ever, the
controller does not help matters, but this is easily remedied with
either a mouse or the new Super CD32 pad.


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ***
@endnode
