@node stri "Striker"

                Striker             Gremlin             £30

How many crap football games do we have to sit through before we get a
decent one for the CD32.  Sensible Soccer had huge possibilities and
missed them.  Striker doesn't even have those possibilities in the first
place.  It features crappy small insignificant graphics, way too fast
action, and bog standard sound (appart from the CD tracks).  It cost £20
more than the floppy version which is also overpriced...  What can I
say??  It's a football game.    YAWN!!


                                                    CD32Bits Rating *
@endnode
@node ulti "Ultimate Body Blows"

         Ultimate Body Blows             Team 17            £30

UBB is by far the best beat 'em up available for the Amiga, and possibly
any other format.  You may think that is a rash statement, but when you
see it, you opinion may well change.  UBB features 22 characters for you
to pick from,  has incredibly detailed backdrops, amazing sound and
speed that MUST be faster than the highly boring Street Fighter 2 Turbo.

The disk has a built in electronic manual, 16 digital tracks and the
option to play with either the normal controller, or a standard
joystick.  In game, there are a huge number of special moves to be had,
and when playing against a friend, the action is at its best.

If you are remotely interested in Beat Em Up's, this is the game for
you, and a must for virtually anyones CD32 game collection.  Of all of
the games available at the moment this is by far the best.  It would
have got full marks if it were not for the control method when using the
CD32 pad.


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ****½
@endnode
@node zool "Zool 2"

                        Zool 2          Gremlin         £30

I wont go into the plot behind Zool, because I am sure that you all have
a good idea what the whole thing is about, but what I will say is that
this effort from Gremlin is much better than the original.  In similar
style to the original Zool, this opens with a Silicon Graphics Rendered
intro which is quite impressive.  That is where the similarities to the
first Zool stop.  The major problem with the first was that it was
enhanced for AGA machines.  Therefore the backgrounds tended to be far
too colourful, and you could often miss objects that needed to be picked
up, much in the style of Oscar.  This release however was designed for
the new(ish) generation of machines, and does not suffer this problem.  

The CD32 version features extra levels, digital soundtracks and two
characters to choose from, although the female one is nowhere near as
easy to use as the original Zool.  The gameplay is simple, and movement
fluid, although if you use the options to have no inertia and Zool in
turbo mode, the sprite is impossible to control.  In conclusion, Zool 2
is a worthy choice if you are looking for a platform game, but at £30 is
a tad expensive.  At the moment, GAME (UK), the computer store is selling the
original Zool for £10, and although it falls short of it's sequel in
quality, it's a much better deal.


                                                    CD32Bits Rating ***
